{"/service/ndnp/nvln/batch_nvln_aurora_ver02/data/sn86076142/00415626940/1908011601/0061.xml":{"full_text":"TONOPAH DAILY BONANZA, TONOPAH, NEVADA, JANUARY 16, 1908.\nEXTENT OF THE\nDAC1TE INTRUSION\nMAKK B. KERR IS AT WORK\nOX AX 1MPOKTAXT\nPROJECT.\nMark B. Kerr, consulting engineer\nfor a number of properties in the\ncamp, lias been inspecting thes\nproperties, and will be at the work\nfor several days yet. Mr. Kerr is en\ngaged at the present, time in the most\nimportant work that was ever know:i\nin the camp, that of determining the\nextent of the dacite intrusion, which\nhas been of so much worry to the\ncamp, and to the stockholders out\nside of the camp. In fact, the East\nern stockholders have been more\nworried than the people in the camp.\nThe important work is going on\nIn the lower levels of the Midway and\nthe Montana Tonopah, where in each\nmine there has been encountered be\nlow the dacite, an ore body, and both\nbodies are very promising.\n\"On the Midway,\" said Mr. Kerr,\n\"below the 800 level we are follow\ning a contact on the edge of one of\nthese dacite tongues, and with great\ner depth, it seems favorable that the\nore will improve in value. At the\nfirst station, one hundred feet below\nthe 800 level, the adjoining quartz\nbody will be prospected, but this will\nnot interfere with the continuous\nsinking. At another 100 feet, pros\npecting will be again continned, and\nit is hoped to obtain higher values\nby this work.\n\"The Montana Tonopah will soon\nresume prospecting at depth on their\nlowest ore body,- the character of\nwhich Is closely allied to this ore\nbody in the Midway.'4 1\nWILL PRODUCE\n\"PASSION PLAY\"\nThe Butler theater, had two more\ncrowded houses last night, the bill\nof the week having made a great hit.\nTonight will be the last night of Dan\niel Boone, and the rest of the good\nthings, including the illustrated song,\n\"Good Old U. S. A.\"\nThe Butler has In preparation a\ngreat treat for the people of Tono\npah. A week from Monday night\nthey will put on \"The Passion Play,'\nand this will run for a week through.\nThe \"Passion Play\" is one of the\nmost remarkable plays ever staged\nIf play, indeed, it may be called. It\nis the reproduction of the passion and\ndeath of our Saviour, which Is pro\nduced in the village of Oberammer\ngau, Bavaria, every ten years, and\npeople flock there from all parts of\nthe world to witness the production.'\nThe moving picture is taken from\nthe last original presentation of the\nwonderful mystery, and Is said to be\nperfect in every detail. There is a\nmile and a half of the film, and the\npictures are hand painted.\nPERSONAL MENTION\nS. H. Gillette leaves for Rawhide\nthis morning.\nGeorge E. Holesworth was a pas\nsenger on the Goldfleld train yester\nday, bound for Reno.\nW. E. Lindsley is back again 'n\nTonopah, having returned from a\nvisit to Philadelphia.\nMajor J. H. Monteath leaves for\nSan Francisco this morning, to be\ngone several days.\nR. P. Dunlap returned from Raw\nhide yesterday, and will leave for\nCarson today or tomorrow.\nMrs. Joseph Sutcliffe was a pas\nsenger on the morning s train yes\nterday, her destination being Raw\nhide, where she goes to join her hus.\nband.\nForest Swears, a well known min\ning man of Goldfleld, was a passen\nger for Blair yesterday morning,\nfrom where he Is going to the new\ncamp of Stimler.\nWalter O'Neil, superintendent of\nthe Farrington properties in Rose\nbud, and formerly of Goldfleld, was\na visitor in the city yesterday, and\nleaves for Rosebud this morning.\nCATHOLIC MARRIAGES.\nBALTIMORE, Md., Jan. 15. Car\ndinal Gibbons said today that the\nnew laws relating to marriage in the\nCatholic church, which have recently\nbeen issued by the holy see, will not\nchange in any important particular\nexisting laws in the church in this\ncountry. The new laws are aimed to\nprevent hasty and Ill-advised mar\nriages. The new regulations will. It\nla said, be announced after Easter.\nA visit to the Nevada Club means\nthat you will be a steady patron.\nYour friends will be there to greet\nyou. tf\nTry H. J. Hall Co. and you won't\npay five times as much in a grocery\ntore. tf\nLITTLE WOMAN\nWITH BIG NERVE\nMRS. IKTSOX BALLIETT, WITH\nCil'X, SCARES OFF ISOLD\nrobber.\nA woman with a little nerve and\na big gun scared on a roDDer trom\nher house on Tuesday night, and if\nshe had been a little less nervous,\nChief of Police Malley might have\nbagged the game, and landed one of\nthe men who have, been burglarizing\nhouses in the town, behind the bars.\nMrs. Letson Balliett was the wo\nman in tne case. Mr. tsauieu nas\nbeen away for a few days, and it is\nmore than possible that this fact be\ncame known to some of the prowling\ngentry of Tonopah. At any rate, on\nthe night in question, Mrs. Balliett'3\nnurse girl called her attention to a I\nnoise on the porch, and as they lis\ntened someone on the porch stumbled\nover a chair. Mrs. Balliett picked un\na revolver and cried: \"Who's\nthere?\"\nThere being no answer, she cried\nagain that she would shoot, and\nthere was a hasty scampering of feet\nand a getaway. Mrs. Balliett tele\nphoned to the police station and\ncaught Chief Malley on the phone.\nShe narrated the incident, and the\nChief said that he would be right up.\nHe was right up, too, but there were\nno signs of the burglar. The Chief\ndeprecated the fact that Mrs. Balliett\nhad made an outcry, as If she had\ntelephoned instead, there would have\nbeen a chance of grabbing the in\ntruder in the act. But Mrs. Balliett\nsaid that she had not thought of\nthat, she was thinking only of the\nman on te porch, and she declared\nthat if he had attempted to get in\nthe window, there would have been\nsomething doing. He was a lucky\nburglar.\nMARCO MI 1 II 11\nAS INTERPRETER\nSUES FOR MONEY DUE\nFROM THE BOYOVICH\nBROTHERS.\nHIM\nM. Milich yesterday recovered a\njudgment against the Boyovich\nbrothers for $60, his attorney fees\nand costs of court. Milich acted as\ninterpreter for the Boyovich broth\ners when their brother was being\ntried for obtaining goods under false\nrepresentations, and he said that they\npromised him $60 for his services.\nWhen the brother was sentenced co\nthe penitentiary for three and a half\nyears, the brothers concluded that\nthe case was over, and refused to pay\nMilich. Judge Brissell, before whom\nthe case was tried yesterday, gave\nthe judgment above referred to. The\nlawyer's fee was $50, and the costs\nwere near that amount.\nTAKING OUT HIGH GRADE.\nThree shifts In all twelve men\nare working on the Davis-Shea lease\non Dexter Union 9. Monday there\nwas $1500 worth of ore taken from\nthese lease workings. The ore run3\nfrom $200 to $1500 per ton In gold,\nand as -much of this as possible will\nbe brought to the surface, every av\nailable place for a man being filled.\nDrifts are being run on the rich\npay streak at both the fifty and the\n100 foot levels. At places the stopes\nhave followed the rich ore to the\ngrass roots and to daylight. The\nstreak varies in width from four in\nches to one foot.\nThe leasers are now arranging for\na hoist, and as soon as this is install\ned a shaft will be sunk to the water\nlevel, where it is believed richer and\nlarger bodies of ore are waiting to\nbe tapped.\nIt will be unnecessary to go\nthrough a painful, expensive opera\ntion for Piles if you use ManZan\nPut up In a collapsible tube with\nnozzle, ready to apply. For any form\nof Plies. Prices 50c For sale by\nTonopah Drug Co.\nThe finest grade of liquors and\ncigars can be found at the Nevada\nClub. tf\nSURE ENOUGH.\n\"Pa,\" asked little Willie, \"if 'cts.\nis short for 'cents,' what's short for\n'dollars?'\n\"All married men at this time of\nthe year, my son.\" responded hia\nfather. Philadelphia Press.\nA WINTER VISITATION.\n\"I'm going to fight the great whit\nplague.\"\n\"What can you do?\"\n\"I can buy a snow shovel, can't I?\nPhiladelphia Public Ledger.\nCorporation seals of every descrip\ntion furnished on the shortest notlca\nby the Bonanza.\nROSEBUD RAPIDLY\nFORGING AHEAD\nFINANCIAL PANIC HAVIXU GONE\nBY ALL PROPERTIES ARK\nRESUMING WORK.\nWalter L. O'Neill, superintendent\nof the Rosebud Extension and the\nSaw Tooth Galena King Mining\ncompanies, was in the city yesterday,\nand will leave for -Rosebud this\nmorning. The properties are owned\nand controlled by. Irving K. Farring\nton Co., of New York, and are of\nthe few on which work was continued\nduring the stress of hard times.\n\"Rosebud has been quiet like near\nly every other district in the State,\"'\nsaid Mr. O'Neil. \"Besides our prop\nerties, work has been going on on the\nSpringfield and' Durango Girl, and\npreparations are being made for the\nresumption of work on other excel\nlent properties, now that the financial\npanic has passed. Nearly every hold\ner In Rosebud made good on the an\nnual assessment work, and there are\nvery few properties open to loca\ntion.\n\"With the little surface work that\nhas been done on the Galena King\nand with the shaft down only forty\nfeet, we have taken out eight tons\nof ore that will go over a hundred\ndollars a ton. This we have had\nready to ship for some time, but de\nelded not to do so on account of\nsmelter conditions. They have made\na strike on the Durango Girl, which\nis near the old Nevada Sulphur Com\npany's mine, which has been working\nfor the last forty years. The strike\nwas made on a drift, and a lead was\ndeveloped which runs from sixty\nounces in silver up into the picture\nvalues.\n\"On the Springfield property\nwhich is controlled by Chicago in\nterests, they are continually getting\nrich pannings, and are now driving\nin a tunnel for 130 feet to catch the\nledge. George Copley and other of\nthe stockholders of the White Alps,\nhave taken a lease on that property,\nand the leasers are going to begin\noperations on a big scale. It is gen\nerally conceded that a little work will\nbring them into shipping ore. When\nthe company ceased operations fo:\nsome unknown reason they were in\nore that went upwards of $85 a ton\n\"The grading on the Western Pa\ncific has been completed, and the\nroad passes within three miles\nthe Saw Tooth and five miles\nof\nRosebud. The company has promis\ned to lay its tracks as soon as the\nweather will permit.\n\"I have not had an opportunity of\ngetting into Rawhide, but I hear of\nthe camp wherever I go. They ar\nfull of it in Reno, and they talked\nof nothing else coming In on the\ntrain. It looks, from all I can hear,\nas if it were going to make a great\ncamp.\"\nSECURES OPTION\nON BANK SALOON\nGOLDF1ELD, Jan. 15. Al North\nof the Golden hotel of Reno, has se\ncured an option on the Bank saloon,\nthe property of the late Charley\nKeidel, and will In all likelihood ex\nercise it. The Bank is one of the\nhandsomest saloons in the State, or,\nfor that matter, anywhere on the\ncoast. It was only recently fitted up\nat a great cost, just prior to Jh\ndeath of Keidel.\nTo stop that pain in the back, that\nstiffness of the joints and muscles,\ntake Pineules. They are guaranteed.\nDon't suffer ftom rheumatism, back\nache, kidney trouble, when you get\n30 days' treatment for $1. A single\ndose at bedtime proves their merits\nGet them today. Sold by Tonopah\nDrug Co.\nMOSQUITO REVOLT ENDS\nGRANADA, Nicaragua, Jan. 8\nThe rising of Mosquito Indians\nagainst the government of President\nKelaya, who was accused by them of\nbeing responsible for the death of\ntheir chief, has been ended. It. was\nof little Importance.\nTHEIR SHYNESS.\nThey were both too shy to marry;\nNow, perhaps, you think that\nfunny;\nBut Louise grew shy of Harry\nWhen she found him shy of money\nPhiladelphia Press.\nA NEW VICTIM.\n\"You say marriage made a new\nman of you, old chap?\"\n\"That's right.\"\n\"Then that wipes out the ten I ow\nyou. Now lend me five, will you?\"\nChicago Journal.\nGo tO H. J. Hall Co. and get\nyour whiskey and save from one\ntwo dollars on the gallon. tf\nNEVADA FIRST NATIONAL BANK OF TONOPAH\nDesignated Depository of the United States\nCAPITAL. (100,000.00 STOCKHOLDERS' LIABILITY, 100 .000.00\nSI.'KPLUS, $50,000.00 TOTAL, 1250.000.00\nOFFICERS AXD DIRECTORS!\nPresident, Malcolm U Macdonald\ni Lewis A. Parkhurst\nVice-Presidents: Donald B. Gillies\nGeorge A. Bartlett\nHon. W. A. Clark, Frank Keith, H. T. Bragdon. Arthur J. Crocker,\nJames H. Monteath. li A. Montgomery, Key Pitt man, John G. Kirchen.\nR. T. Harris, Cashier\nRing's Little Liver Pills wake up\nlazy livers, clean the system and\nclear the skin. Try them for bilious\nness and sick headache. Price 25c.\nSold by Tonopah Drug Co.\nNEW ADVERTISEMENTS.\nANNUAL REPORT\nOF THE\nBULLFROG REDUCTION\nWATER COMPANY\nJanuary 15, 1908.\nThe following is a statement of the\nbusiness transacted during the year\n1907, by the above named Company\nTotal receipts from all\nsourceB $68,730.53\nTotal expenditures $87,122.04\nI certify that the foregoing state\nment is correct.\nOLIVER WREN,\n1-15 6t Secretary and Treasurer\nANNUAL REPORT\nOF THE\nSHOSHONE POLARIS\nMINING COMPANY\nJanuary 15, 1908.\nThe following is a statement of the\nbusiness transacted during the year\n1907, by the above named Company:\nTotal receipts from all\nsources 5.965.4S\nTotal expenditures $11,084.07\nI certify that the foregoing state\nment Is correct.\nB. W. TURNER,\n1-15 6t Secretary,\nANNUAL REPORT\nOF THE\nMONTGOMERY SHOSHONE\nMINES COMPANY\nJanuary 15, 1908.\nThe following is a statement of the\nbusiness transacted during the year\n1907, by the above named Company\nTotal receipts from all\nsources $176,714.3\nTotal expenditures .$170,580.8\ncertify that the foregoing state\nment is correct.\nOLIVER WREN,\n1-15 6t Secretary and Treasurer!\nANNUAL STATEMENT\nOK THE\nSILVER PEAK BLUE JAY\nMINING COMPANY\nFor the year ending December 31st,\n1907.\nLocation of mine, Silver Peak Min\ning District, County of Nye, Stiste of\nNevada.\nDEBIT. I\nJanuary 1, 1907, to cash\non hand 1,595.33\nTo amount received from\nother sources 18,